<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-759-438  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 759 438.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 10 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Amstrad blamed for Australian dealer crash.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Atkins, Gavin.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Amstrad Consumer Electronics PLC (contracts)Everything Computer (finance).andO;Topic:     Financial StabilityCompaniesDealers and AgentsBankruptcy.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AMSTRAD BLAMED FOR AUSTRALIAN DEALER CRASH ADELAIDE, AUSTRALIA, 1989 OCT 4(NB) -- The owner of South Australia's largest Amstrad dealership has blamedAmstrad for the collapse of his company.andM;Hans Kroonenburg of Everything Computer said that the high failure rate ofAmstrad high-end PCs caused his company to go broke, and he would now have tosell his Adelaide home to pay off debts.andP;  &quot;We had a failure rate of 90percent, with some machines coming back five times.andP;  The associatedsupport-costs put us under,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;Amstrad executives advised us they were going to recall all the 286s butnothing happened.andP;  They told me the machines were faulty four months ago,&quot; hesaid.andP;  Kroonenburg said he was taking legal advice as to whether he has theright to sue Amstrad.andM;The Australian sales and marketing director of Amstrad, Bordan Tkachuk, saidthere were no grounds on which Kroonenburg could take legal action and saidthe business failure was just the beginning of many small company collapsesdue to a softening of the local PC market.andM;(Gavin Atkins andamp; Computing Australia/19891004)</TEXT></DOC>